European Restaurant Deepdive

Project Report for STAT 303-1 Fall 2024

Author

Robert Yao, Grace Wu, Yingshan Chen, Maddie Wang

Published

December 10, 2024

Abstract
In this report, we analyze dining trends across Europe, focusing on the distribution of top-rated restaurants and factors influencing restaurant ratings, such as cuisine preferences. The analysis reveals that while award-winning restaurants often provide exceptional experiences, relying solely on the number of awards does not capture the full picture. In particular, some countries, despite having a high number of awards, also have a significant proportion of low ratings. Regional preferences play a key role, with certain countries excelling in specific types of cuisine, while others show lower ratings for particular international cuisines. Based on these findings, we recommend that tourists consider the overall distribution of ratings and regional culinary variations when selecting restaurants while abroad. This approach provides a more comprehensive understanding of dining quality and ensures more satisfying experiences. However, as culinary trends evolve, continuous evaluation is necessary to account for shifts in customer preferences and dining landscapes across Europe.

1) Inspiration

As passionate foodies, we love diving into different cultures through their cuisines, and Europe is at the top of all our travel bucket lists. For two of us, it would be our first time, while the other two are eager to return for more delicious discoveries. This project offers us a data-driven approach to plan the ultimate foodie trip across Europe, making sure we experience the must-visit spots recommended by both locals and fellow travelers in the most mouthwateringly satisfying way. At a broader level, we think this data would be helpful for restaurants to benchmark themselves in the market, and create a baseline for what they should improve on to stay profitable.

2) Problem Statements

  • Robert: Are award-winning European restaurants a worthwhile experience for tourists?
    • In order to answer this, I will analyze whether award-winning European restaurants are truly better across relevant categories than non-award-winning European restaurants. In addition, I will analyze how these award-winning restaurants are distributed geographically in order to determine accessibility to tourists.
  • Grace: What are the most popular cuisines across Europe, and how do the average ratings of restaurants differ by cuisine?
    • I would categorize restaurants according to cuisine type to analyze and compare their average ratings. It would also be valuable to explore variations in ratings between regions and examine the distribution of restaurants by cuisine in different parts of Europe for a more nuanced view of dining preferences and trends.
  • Yingshan: How strongly is a restaurantâs average rating correlated with its award winning status and should it affect where you visit?
    • Since the dataset includes average ratings, I would first categorize the restaurants based on whether they have received an award, and then analyze the correlation coefficients between these awards and their average ratings. It would be helpful to analyze whether recieving more awards is correlated to the average ratings and where they are located.
  • Maddie: What country has the restaurants with the highest average ratings?
    • Since each reviewer on TripAdvisor can assign a restaurant to one of five rating categories (terrible, poor, average, very good, or excellent), I will assign each restaurant a highest voted rating based on the mode vote. I will then analyze how these rating categories are distributed across countries to determine which countries have the highest (and lowest-rated) restaurants. To enhance this analysis, I will create a map to visualize where the top-rated restaurants are in Europe.

3) Data

We used the âTripadvisor European Restaurantsâ dataset from Kaggle. Tripadvisor is a travel guidance platform that helps people plan, book, and take trips. This specific dataset hones in on restaurants with attributes such as location, average rating, number of reviews, cuisine types etc. The data was retrieved through Tripadvisor by Stefano Leone, and covers a wide range of restaurants in the main countries in Europe.

Citation: Leone, Stefano. âTripAdvisor European Restaurants.â Kaggle, 18 May 2021, www.kaggle.com/datasets/stefanoleone992/tripadvisor-european-restaurants.

  • 1,083,397 observations
    • Each observation represents a restaurant, with each column/variable being a different descriptor for the restaurant (ex: country, address, cuisines).
  • 42 total variables
    • 17 continuous
    • 25 categorical
    • Collectively, our group used 17 of the 42 variables.

4) Stakeholders

Stakeholders in this project include both tourists eager to discover top-rated restaurants across Europe and local residents seeking new dining experiences in their area. By analyzing restaurant ratings and mapping their locations, we can provide clear and organized analyses and visualizations of dining options available in each European country. Additionally, both prospective and current restaurant owners would benefit from this project by gaining valuable insights into market trends, customer preferences, and the competitive landscape, helping them make informed decisions about location, menu offerings, and customer engagement.

5) Data Cleaning

5.1) Cleaning 1

By Robert Yao

There were two components to my analysis: a comparison of ratings and a geographical distribution. I will discuss my data cleaning approach for both components separately. First:

Component 1 (Rating comparison):

Before analysis, I noticed that between the three rating variables of interest, food, service, and value, about 45% of the observations had missing data in at least one of the variables. I did not look too much at each individual rating variable because the numbers were quite similar and observations missing one tended to miss the other (although this was not 100% the case).

I chose to group by region, avg_rating, and award_bin as I believed using these categories would provide greater accuracy in my imputation than just one. I believed that just one would not capture the whole picture. Using region was important because the cultural context as well as surrounding competition influences a dinerâs perspective on restaurants. For instance, how a diner would rate the food at a restaurant in the French countryside would likely be different from how they would rate the food in the midst of London. This hypothetical thinking could be applied across any of the three categories I was imputing. Thus, I thought region would influence a dinerâs perception and thus rating, making for an important grouping variable.

However, I also knew that just region would not be enough. Consider a horrible quality restaurant next to a great restaurant in the same region. This can occur, so I needed to also group by something that would capture the quality of the restaurant overall. For this, I looked to the variable avg_rating, a less granular rating factor for each restaurant. With just this variable, however, I would not be able to capture cultural and geographical contexts. Thus, I used both. Additionally, I included award_bin because that was my main category of analysis and I did not want to muddy the analysis by imputing across category. I tested imputation both with and without award_bin and found that both methods imputed the same quantity of data; the inclusion simply made the imputation more accurate.

I used mean imputation by group, as this made sense applied to a large dataset of ratings. Numeric mean tends to perform well with large quantities of data, and imputation by averaging ratings across a group where other factors are similar seems logically sound. After imputation, only 13% of the observations had missing data in at least one of the three factors, which means there was at most 13% data missing from the analysis. This seemed acceptable, as there were still nearly 950,000 good rows to perform analysis on.

There were no outliers because the scale is restricted from 1 to 5 for these variables. Categories were not of particular significance in terms of data cleaning within this component, besides what I discussed above when using them as grouping variables. Even then, the number of categories was not of interest to the imputation process. There were no categories that were not useful nor any incorrect data.

Now, onto:

Component 2 (Geographical distribution):

One thing I noticed was that 15,790 observations of data had missing latitude/longitude data. I considered imputing it, as some of these observations had non-missing identifiable variables like region, province, city, and even address. I could have used this information to approximate latitude/longitude. However, I realized that this would have taken significant effort so I wanted to check if it would have been worth it in the first place.

Considering I was focusing on French and Italian award-winning restaurants for my mapping visualization rather than ALL European restaurants (reasons discussed later), I double checked how many observations were missing for my category of interest. I found that only 58 award-winning French restaurants had missing lat/long data while there were 43,250 total award-winning French restaurants; only 0.13% missing. This percentage is even lower for Italy, being 37 missing observations out of 65,488, a missing percentage of only 0.06%. Considering the effort required, I thought it was not optimal to impute this data.

Outliers did not apply in this component. Categories were not of particular significance in terms of data cleaning within this component. There were no incorrect values. Additionally, I utilized Statista data [1], [2] to generate data for populations and popularly available latitude/longitude data for city locations.

5.2) Cleaning 2

By Grace Wu

From the original dataset, the following columns were considered: ârestaurant_name,â âcountry,â âcuisines,â and âavg_rating.â Of these, approximately 15.6% of the âcuisinesâ data and 8.9% of the âavg_ratingâ data were missing. Additionally, 3.6% of the data had missing values in both columns. The ârestaurant_nameâ and âcuisinesâ columns were normalized to lowercase and stripped of whitespace.

Cleaning âcuisinesâ and âavg_ratingâ

The âcuisinesâ column contained categorical data with numerous variations in how restaurants were categorized (likely using a method similar to tags). Missing values in âcuisinesâ were dropped, as they represented only a small portion of the dataset and imputation would require external research beyond the available data. To standardize the âcuisinesâ column and prepare it for analysis, categories were consolidated by retaining the (global) most frequent label for each restaurant. This step was necessary before addressing the âavg_ratingâ column, where the mean rating for each cuisine was later calculated. Further details on data wrangling âcuisinesâ are provided in the Data Analysis section.

Once the âcuisinesâ column was cleaned and standardized, missing âavg_ratingâ values were imputed using the mean rating for each cuisine. After imputation, a small number of missing values remained, as some cuisine categories had no available ratings. These rows were then dropped. Given the minimal impact on the overall dataset, this approach was appropriate, though the results should be interpreted with this limitation in mind.

Addressing Outliers

Lastly, the âavg_ratingâ column contains outliers, particularly when grouped by cuisine type revealed in the analysis below. These outliers were included for a more nuanced analysis, as excluding them might obscure meaningful patterns in the data.

5.3) Cleaning 3

By Yingshan Chen

Handling Missing Values

In the dataset, several variables used for analysis exhibit missing values:

  • âavg_ratingâ has 8.92% missing values.
  • âawardsâ has 75.71% missing values.

Imputation for âavg_ratingâ

The missing values in the âavg_ratingâ column are imputed using the mean of the column. Given the large size of the dataset (nearly a million datapoints), the impact of imputing with the mean is minimal and does not significantly affect the overall analysis. The mean value is a reasonable and efficient choice because it represents a generalized average that maintains the distribution of ratings while being computationally simple. This method ensures that we can proceed with the analysis without losing valuable data, while still providing meaningful results.

Imputation for âawardsâ

The missing values in the âawardsâ column are handled differently. For NaN values, we impute them with a value of 0, indicating that the restaurant did not have any awards. This approach makes sense given that the primary focus of the analysis is the number of awards, not the specific types of awards.

Additionally, since the âawardsâ column is a string containing either a single award name or a list of awards, further cleaning is necessary. A user defined function is implemented to split the string by commas to analyze the number of awards correctly. This step allows us to quantify the awards, which is crucial for our analysis.

Outliers and Incorrect Values

Upon reviewing the numeric variables, no outliers or incorrect values (such as negative ratings or zero values for relevant metrics) were found in the dataset. Therefore, there was no need to handle or exclude any outliers.

Categorical Variables

The analysis also includes categorical variables, particularly the âawardsâ column, which consists of multiple award categories. While the exact types of awards are not critical for this analysis (as we are only concerned with the count of awards), it is important to ensure that each restaurant is appropriately categorized based on the number of awards they have.

Handling Irrelevant Categories

In this case, the specific award names are irrelevant to the analysis. Therefore, we focus only on counting the number of awards for each restaurant. This avoids unnecessary complexity in the model while preserving the key information needed for the analysis.

5.4) Cleaning 4

By Maddie Wang

My data cleaning process can be broken down into two steps:

Part 1: Finding how many restaurants have missing ratings

My data analysis focused on the five categorical ratings columns (terrible, poor, average, very good, and excellent), where each numerical value for a restaurant represented the number of reviewers who felt that rating best reflected the restaurantâs overall quality. The five categories had the same number of missing values, implying that there were simply some restaurants that were not given ratings, meaning all the rating columns were useful to me.

In total, there were 95,193 restaurants with missing ratings, which equals to around 8.78% of the total number of restaurants in the dataset. Ultimately, I felt that imputing was not a possibility, as each row represents a distinct restaurant, and there are no correlations to any other categories. Though I considered imputing an overall highest-voted rating based on the mode of similar sized restaurants or similar location restaurants, I felt that each restaurant was too distinct. Based on my own personal experiences, the rating that best reflects each restaurant is specific to my experience at that individual restaurant, and there is a wide variety in quality that can be found at similar sizes or locations.

Given the nature of the rating method, there are no outliers or incorrect values, and therefore I did not need to exclude any restaurants that had rating data from my analysis.

Overall, based on the fact that the percent of restaurants missing ratings was quite small (8.78%) and that there was no statistically reliable method to impute the data, I decided to proceed with the data analysis without further cleaning. However, I recognized that the distribution of missing restaurant ratings may vary across countries, so I added an extra layer of analysis such that stakeholders could be cognisant of which countries may have a less representative analysis.

Part 2: Analyzing how the restaurants with missing ratings are distributed across countries

After extracting all the restaurants with missing ratings, I grouped them by country and calculated the percentage breakdown to see which countries had the highest and lowest percentages of restaurants with missing ratings. The top three countries were Slovakia (18.89%), Romania (17.88%), and Poland (15.87%), meaning there is the most room for statistical error in the findings of the restaurant ratings in these select three countries. On the other hand, the bottom three countries were Croatia (5.99%), Scotland (6.08%), and Wales (6.40%), and therefore these countries should have the smallest statistical error.

6) Data Analysis

6.1) Analysis 1

By Robert Yao

As discussed earlier, I approached my question from two angles: 1) Are award-winning restaurants better? 2) Are award-winning restaurants convenient/accessible to visit?

As with before, I will start by discussing my methodology and results for the first approach.

Component 1 (Rating comparison):

I wanted to compare the award and non-award subsets of the data. Thus, I divided the dataframe into these subsets by creating a categorical variable that marked each observation as having or not having an award, award_bin. Using this new variable as the identifier, I then melted the data. Because I was interested in comparing restaurants across three key metrics (food quality, service excellence, and value), I used these three variables in the data as categories for a new variable in my long dataframe titled rating_type. I did this in order to reshape the data in a way where I could compare award-winning and non-award-winning restaurants across these three performance metrics. Now, all I needed to do with the long dataframe was to aggregate and perform calculations.

I grouped by both award_bin and rating_type, since that created my separated groups of interest. After all, I wanted to compare between award and non-award, and I wanted to compare on three different rating types. I then found the mean of the numeric rating value for each group and reset the index for restructuring. This concluded the wrangling required for my analysis.

I next moved onto visually representing the data. The message was conveyed best through a side-by-side barplot:

We see that across the board, award-winning restaurants across Europe tend to perform better than non-award-winning restaurants. This affirms that visiting award-winning restaurants, on average, will yield the diner a better experience in the most relevant ways.

Itâs also interesting to take a closer look at the differences in each rating type. We see that the differences between award and non-award restaurants in average rating across food, service, and value are 0.28, 0.26, and 0.20 respectively. Notably, the difference is smallest in value. Perhaps, this is because many award-winning restaurants tend to be fine-dining establishments that are lower value per dollar but are more likely to win awards. Food and service are better at similar scales for award-winning restaurants. These differences are not insignificant on a 5 point scale.

This provides evidence to prospective tourists that they might find more meaningful and fulfilling experiences exploring award-winning restaurants, at least on average.

With this information, I now wanted to know whether these award-winning restaurants would be accessible for tourists, which led me to:

Component 2 (Geographical distribution):

I decided to utilize latitude and longitude data to create a map visualization. For these maps, I chose to focus on France and Italy. Looking at the dataset, I found that Italy, England, and France were the three countries with the most award-winning restaurants. I chose to exclude England because of its small geographical size. In addition to their larger sizes, Italy and France both have a rich history, culture, and pride surrounding their cuisines. Italy also has the benefit of containing the greatest quantity of award-winning restaurants (65488) while many of the most prestigious culinary awards (like Michelin) originated in France. Focusing on these two countries will allow for more in-depth analysis; a map of all of Europe would provide far too much information to extract knowledge.

An important step in creating these map visualizations is converting latitude and longitude information into usable data. To do this, I used function GeoDataFrame from the geopandas library. As an input, I provided the appropriate Coordinate Reference System. This utilizes lat/lon data to generate a geometry variable that can then be plotted. I ran the data, as well as additional dataframes containing information on city locations and populations, through this function. These additional dataframes contain information from Statista.

I then created subsets of the original restaurant geodataframe, one for award-winning French restaurants and one for award-winning Italian restaurants. Letâs first take a look at Franceâs distribution:

Within the map, red dots represent award-winning restaurants and some of the largest French cities are marked by a circle. The size of this circle depends on that cityâs population; the larger the population, the larger the circle. We see that there are award-winning restaurants all across France, but we see that they are particularly concentrated around large, populated cities especially Paris, as well as somewhat along the southern and eastern coasts. Notably, every large city highlighted in the map has a concentration of award-winning restaurants. Tourists are already likely to visit these urban areas.

Letâs take a moment to focus on the two larger regions with concentrations of award-winning restaurants. One, I believe, is Paris. This is generally on every touristâs itinerary when they travel to France. Another is the southeast corner of France, or the French Riviera (CÃ´te dâAzur). Notably, this is also one of the most popular French vacation destinations, known for its beautiful nature and beaches. We thus see that award-winning restaurants tend to be concentrated in locations where tourists tend to visit already, at least in France.

Now, Italy:

Italy seems to have a more uniform distribution than France. But still, looking at each of the largest cities, we see a high concentration of red within each circle. This indicates that, like France, large cities have many award-winning restaurants. And these large cities are easy for tourists to reach. In addition, there are many award-winning restaurants in northern Italy. Northern Italy tends to attract more tourists than southern Italy, as many of the most famous landmarks and cities are in the north (Venice, the Alps, Florence, etc.).

In both France and Italy, we see that award-winning restaurants are concentrated around areas that tourists tend to visit. This indicates that they are likely accessible and convenient, in addition to being generally better than non-award-winning restaurants. Thus, all in all, we can indicate that award-winning restaurants are likely a worthwhile experience for tourists and diners.

6.2) Analysis 2

By Grace Wu

Methodology

To prepare the data for visualization, the âcuisinesâ column was wrangled to standardize the cuisine labels for each restaurant. The original âcuisinesâ column contained multiple labels per restaurant, often separated by commas. The first step involved splitting the values in this column by commas, resulting in a list of all cuisines mentioned for each restaurant.

Next, the frequency of each cuisine type was counted across the entire dataset. To ensure consistency and facilitate analysis, each restaurantâs list of cuisines was mapped to the most frequent cuisine type found in the global dataset. This was achieved by identifying the most common cuisine label for each restaurant, based on the overall frequency of each cuisine in the entire dataset. In cases where a restaurant had multiple cuisine labels, the most frequent cuisine label across all restaurants was chosen to represent that restaurant.

This approach was chosen for several reasons: - Simplicity: It provides a clear, singular cuisine label for each restaurant, simplifying the analysis and visualization process. - Consistency: By using the global most frequent label, the complexity introduced by multiple overlapping or variably named cuisine categories is minimized. - Data integrity: This method retains the most representative cuisine type for each restaurant while reducing noise caused by variations in the dataset.

This wrangling step was essential in creating a uniform dataset, allowing for meaningful comparisons of cuisine distributions and their relationships with other variables, such as average ratings, across the dataset.

1) Bar Chart: Distribution of Restaurants by Cuisine

To analyze the distribution of restaurants across different cuisine types, the frequency of each cuisine category was calculated. A bar plot was created to visualize the number of restaurants that fall under each cuisine type. For a clearer view of the most common types of restaurants in the dataset, only cuisines with counts greater than 200 were included in the visualization.

From the resulting bar chart, it is evident that Italian cuisine dominates the dataset, followed by European cuisine and Cafes. The chart also highlights the disproportionate representation of certain cuisines, which can influence the analysis of restaurant ratings and other related variables.

These results provide a better understanding of the concentration of restaurant types in the dataset and serve as the foundation for further analysis on cuisine ratings and regional trends.

3) Heatmap: Average Rating by Cuisine and Country

The heatmap below visualizes the average ratings by cuisine and country, providing a clear view of how different types of cuisine perform across various European countries. This allows for an exploration of regional trends, highlighting which cuisines are most highly rated in specific countries and uncovering any regional preferences or discrepancies in restaurant ratings. The heatmap also gives insights into cuisine-country combinations that stand out with unusually high or low ratings, providing a deeper understanding of how dining experiences can vary across both cuisine types and locations.

Itâs important to note that the heatmap highlights the diversity in restaurant ratings, with some countries consistently offering high ratings for certain types of cuisines, while other cuisines struggle to perform well across multiple regions. This helps identify potential regional factors that might influence the success or failure of specific cuisines in particular countries.

From the heatmap, several key observations can be made. Algerian cuisine in Germany and Hokkaido cuisine in The Netherlands both stand out with mean ratings of 1.0, indicating very poor performance or potential data quality issues. On the other end of the spectrum, a number of cuisines, such as African cuisines in Bulgaria and Slovakia, show a mean rating of 5.0, suggesting that these regions consistently offer high-quality dining experiences for these particular cuisines. Cuisines with extremely low ratings like Algerian in Germany and Hokkaido in The Netherlands likely represent either limited sample sizes (only a few restaurants) or anomalous data, and further investigation may be necessary to understand the underlying causes of such low scores.

Some other observations include: - Chinese cuisine has the highest mean rating of 4.16 in Bulgaria, with relatively consistent ratings across other countries, suggesting either a standard level of quality or similar preference for Chinese restaurants across different regions. - American cuisine follows a similar trend with a high mean rating of 4.17 in Greece.

This heatmap and the numeric results highlight both regional culinary preferences and variability in restaurant quality across cuisines and countries. By considering both the visual and numeric outcomes, it becomes apparent that certain cuisine-country combinations outperform others, while some cuisines, such as Algerian and Hokkaido, struggle in particular markets.

4) Summary Results

The analysis reveals key trends about the most popular cuisines across Europe and how restaurant ratings differ by cuisine type. Through the boxplot and heatmap analyses, we can identify patterns that speak to both popularity and dining experiences across Europe.

1. Most Popular Cuisines and Rating Distribution by Cuisine

From the boxplot analysis, Neapolitan cuisine emerges as a standout, with consistently high ratings and a very narrow spread, indicating a high level of consistency in the quality of Neapolitan restaurants across different countries. In contrast, Kyoto cuisine shows a similarly high median but with more variability in ratings, as indicated by a larger standard deviation, suggesting greater variability in the quality of restaurants serving Kyoto-style dishes.

On the other hand, Slovenian cuisine, represented by only a single restaurant in the dataset, provides limited insight due to its small sample size, with an extremely low median rating that should be interpreted with caution. Both Chinese and American cuisines have lower median ratings, accompanied by higher variability (larger interquartile ranges) and outliers. This suggests that both Chinese and American restaurants show a wider spectrum of dining experiences, with some highly rated restaurants but also a significant portion of low-rated ones. Fast Food emerges with a particularly high number of outliers, indicating a mixed quality range within this category, where both excellent and poor-quality restaurants coexist.

The boxplot analysis highlights not only the central tendency of ratings but also the variability and presence of outliers within each cuisine category. These insights suggest that while some cuisines, like Neapolitan, tend to provide consistently high dining experiences, others, like Fast Food, exhibit more significant disparities in restaurant quality across Europe.

2. Regional Preferences and Cross-Country Trends

The heatmap further adds depth to this analysis by visualizing the average ratings by cuisine and country. It shows how different European countries have distinct preferences for various cuisines, and how cuisine ratings vary across countries.

Key findings from the heatmap include: - Algerian cuisine in Germany and Hokkaido cuisine in The Netherlands have the lowest ratings at 1.0, likely due to limited sample sizes. These extremely low ratings should be treated with caution and may not represent broader trends. - In contrast, many cuisines show mean ratings of 5.0 in specific countries, reflecting regional preferences or the presence of high-quality specialized restaurants that dominate the ratings for these cuisines. - Chinese cuisine displays relatively consistent ratings across countries, with a particularly high mean of 4.16 in Bulgaria, and American cuisine has a high mean rating of 4.17 in Greece, indicating possible regional trends.

These findings demonstrate that certain cuisines have a stronger presence and higher ratings in specific countries, with regional preferences influencing the success of certain cuisines. The heatmap reveals that neighboring countries can share similar highly rated cuisines, such as African cuisines in Bulgaria and Slovakia.

Methodology:

Grouping and Aggregating the data:

Purpose: The data is grouped by restaurant_link, which is a unique identifier for each restaurant to account for restaurants having multiple locations. For each group, the following aggregation is performed: - restaurant_name: The first restaurant name in each group is taken (as it should be consistent across the same restaurant link). - num_awards: The total number of awards is computed by summing the num_awards column for each group. - avg_ratings: The maximum average rating is chosen, although it does not matter since the âavg_ratingâ is already the restaurants average.

Reasoning: This aggregation allows us to summarize the data by restaurant, turning it from a âlongâ format into a âwideâ format with a single entry per restaurant. This step is important for analyzing trends and relationships between variables, such as the number of awards and ratings.

8) Conclusion

Tourists should be cautious about placing too much emphasis on the number of awards each country has received, as every country has its own unique strengths and cuisine preferences. While award-winning restaurants are often exceptional and conveniently located for travelers, selecting countries to visit based solely on the number of awards may not provide the full picture.

A more insightful approach would be to consider the distribution of rating categories, particularly the highest-rated categories. For instance, although England secured the second-highest number of awards, it also has the highest proportion of restaurants rated as âterribleâ among all the countries in the dataset. This contrast highlights the importance of looking beyond awards to understand the broader quality spectrum of a countryâs dining scene.

The cuisine-specific analysis also reveals that some countries show significant regional preferences, which may influence a travelerâs dining experience. For example, countries like Bulgaria and Slovakia have exceptionally high ratings for African cuisine, while countries like Germany and the Netherlands show very low ratings for Algerian and Hokkaido cuisines.

In conclusion, while accolades provide some insight into the quality of dining in a country, tourists should also consider other factors, including regional cuisine preferences and the variability in the percentage of rating categories. By examining the broader distribution of restaurant ratings and understanding the unique culinary landscape of each country, tourists can make more informed decisions about their dining experiences across Europe.
